visual, a simple triangle

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:37.260 align:middle line:10%
and then a reverse
one put on top.

00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:39.850 align:middle line:10%
So you have a
symbol that's common

00:12:39.850 --> 00:12:42.040 align:middle line:10%
taught as the Star
of David or so on.

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:44.850 align:middle line:10%
And then if you add
little triangles

00:12:44.850 --> 00:12:47.530 align:middle line:10%
on the next scale
on the next level,

00:12:47.530 --> 00:12:50.610 align:middle line:10%
then you'll have little Stars
of Davids that are developing.

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:52.950 align:middle line:84%
And then you can keep
adding little triangles

00:12:52.950 --> 00:12:53.879 align:middle line:90%
and little triangles.

00:12:53.879 --> 00:12:56.420 align:middle line:84%
And then you zoom in, and then
keep adding them, and zoom in.

00:12:56.420 --> 00:12:58.290 align:middle line:84%
And you can go like
that to infinity.

00:12:58.290 --> 00:13:01.320 align:middle line:84%
The complexity can become
very, very complex.

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:04.140 align:middle line:84%
Now that's a simple
geometry fractal structure,

00:13:04.140 --> 00:13:08.460 align:middle line:84%
but there is more complex
geometry fractal structure

00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:09.720 align:middle line:90%
that are beautiful.

00:13:09.720 --> 00:13:12.900 align:middle line:84%
The Mandelbrot
set-- for instance--

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:18.360 align:middle line:84%
from Benoit Mandelbrot, that
was a very strong influence

00:13:18.360 --> 00:13:21.930 align:middle line:84%
